Section section_02 (Chars 8283–11523):
Section Summary: The village of Barcy was heavily damaged during the war, with the church and several houses reduced to ruins. The Mayor and his family took shelter in their cellar for six days, enduring constant shelling. The narrator was later granted permission to visit Châlons, Vitry, and Bar-le-Duc, and was given a letter of introduction to facilitate their trip. They traveled to these destinations, observing many soldiers at the train station and on military trains, and were struck by the height and health of the French officers they met. The narrator was eager to experience the war firsthand, having been in Paris for three months with little evidence of the conflict beyond wounded soldiers in the streets.
